"""
MKT Context Commentary — Mark chapters 5–6
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-mark-5-6.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/mark.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/mark.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/ellicott/mark.json (philological notes)

Key decisions in this range:
- Mark written for Roman Gentile audience (ca. 65-70 CE); Peter as source (Papias)
- Decapolis setting confirms Gentile territory throughout ch.5:1-20
- Leviticus 15 impurity framework essential for 5:25-34
- Legion = Roman military unit (~6,000); naming choice carries political freight
- Talitha koum preserved in Aramaic: Papias tradition of Peter's exact words
- Herod Antipas's title was technically tetrarch (not king) per Josephus Ant. 18
- "Passing by" (parelthein) in 6:48 echoes the theophany language of Exod 33/1 Kgs 19
- Groups of 50/100 in feeding recall Moses's Sinai military organization (Exod 18)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MARK = {
  "5": {
    "1": '<p>The Decapolis (Ten Cities) was a league of Hellenistic cities east and southeast of the Sea of Galilee — largely Gentile territory. The presence of a large herd of pigs (v.11) confirms the Gentile setting: pig-keeping was forbidden under Levitical law and would not occur in Jewish territory. The encounter with the Gerasene demoniac is the first extended Gentile healing in Mark, foreshadowing the Gentile mission. The name Legion (v.9) is explicitly Roman: a Roman legion comprised approximately 6,000 soldiers — the demonic power takes the name of the occupying imperial force.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The tombs as a dwelling place signal extreme social exclusion: contact with the dead made a person ritually impure for seven days under Levitical law (Num 19:16), and a person who lived among the tombs would be perpetually in a state of uncleanness, unable to enter a village or participate in communal life. The man\'s habitation in the tombs is not merely an image of isolation but a legal condition — he was excluded from every institution of Jewish society. Approaching Jesus from the tombs underscores what kind of person Jesus was willing to engage.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Chains and restraints were the ancient world\'s primary (and only) response to violent mental disturbance. There was no treatment — only containment. The repeated failures of binding (he tore the chains) would have been read against the background of Second Temple Jewish and Greco-Roman demonology, in which certain possessing spirits were understood to grant superhuman strength. The man\'s condition was not merely unusual but had exhausted the community\'s entire capacity to manage him.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The detail about broken chains and shattered fetters serves as a narrative proof of the severity of the possession and the inadequacy of human remedies. The community has tried and repeatedly failed. This sets up the contrast: what chains could not accomplish, a word from Jesus will achieve. For Mark\'s Roman audience, the imagery of inescapable chains suddenly snapped would have registered as a power demonstration of the most concrete kind.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Night and day, in the tombs and in the mountains, crying out and cutting himself with stones — the picture is of unrelenting torment with no rest and no audience except the hills. Self-cutting (or self-laceration) was associated in the ancient world with prophetic ecstasy and mourning rituals (cf. 1 Kgs 18:28, where the prophets of Baal cut themselves). Here the act is a symptom of uncontrolled internal violence turned outward. The man had become his own enemy, with no power to stop himself.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The demoniac runs and falls in prostration (prosekynēsen) before Jesus — the same gesture of submission that Mark uses for Jairus (5:22), the Syrophoenician woman (7:25), and the disciples at the Transfiguration. The prostration from a distance registers the power differential: the demon-possessed man cannot approach the one before whom the forces controlling him must kneel. This involuntary reverence from the demonic side is a consistent feature of Mark\'s exorcism accounts (cf. 1:24, 3:11).</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Son of the Most High God" (hyie tou theou tou hypsistou) is a Gentile form of divine address. "Most High" (Hypsistos) was a title used in the Hellenistic world for the supreme deity across multiple religious traditions — it appears in Greek inscriptions from Syria and Phoenicia as a generic monotheistic title accessible to both Jews and Gentiles. The adjuration "in God\'s name don\'t torture me" follows the pattern of ancient magical adjuration formulas, in which a lesser spiritual power attempts to bind a greater one by invoking a divine name. The demon is trying (and failing) to use Jesus\'s own God against him.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Mark\'s editorial note — "for Jesus had said to him, \'Come out\'" — places the demoniac\'s prostration and adjuration as a response to an already-issued exorcism command. The demon\'s elaborate resistance is thus not a negotiation Jesus is open to but a defeated power\'s final thrashing. This sequence is consistent with Mark\'s exorcism pattern: the command is given once and is effective; the manifestations of resistance are symptoms of departure, not signs of failure.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The name Legion is one of the most politically charged moments in the Gospel. A Roman legion was the primary military unit of the Roman army, comprising approximately 6,000 infantry plus cavalry and support — roughly the garrison that would have been stationed in the region. The demon takes the name of the dominant occupying power. For Mark\'s Roman audience this naming would have been both bold and recognizable: the forces that tormented this man in the tombs bear the name of the forces that ruled the empire. The irony is structural — Legion, which no one could bind, will be cast into swine.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The demons\' plea not to be sent "out of the area" (out of the country, chōra) reflects a widespread ancient belief that spiritual powers were territorially bound — each region had its associated spirits, and expulsion from a territory meant displacement into a powerless limbo. This belief appears in various forms in Jewish literature (1 Enoch, Jubilees) and Greco-Roman demonology. Jesus\'s exorcisms are not merely personal healings but territorial assertions: he has authority over every region he enters, including Gentile Decapolis.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The large herd of pigs grazing on the hillside is the clearest possible marker that this is Gentile territory. Leviticus 11:7 prohibited pigs as unclean animals; no observant Jewish community would maintain a pig herd. The Decapolis cities were Hellenistic foundations (many established by Alexander\'s successors) whose populations were primarily Gentile. The economic scale — two thousand pigs (v.13) — indicates a substantial commercial operation, making the loss not merely dramatic but financially significant for the region.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The demons\' request to be sent into the pigs rather than expelled entirely reflects the same territorial logic as v.10: they are bargaining for continued presence in the region, even in a degraded host. The pigs are available, numerous, and legally unclean — from the demons\' perspective, an acceptable alternative. Jesus grants the request, but the result is not the prolonged presence the demons sought: the pigs rush into the lake and drown. The bargain collapses immediately.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The herd of roughly two thousand rushing down the steep bank into the lake echoes the drowning of the Egyptian army in the Sea of Reeds (Exod 14:28) — a connection Mark\'s audience may or may not have caught, but which belongs to a consistent Exodus-and-new-liberation pattern in the Gospel. The Sea of Galilee (fresh water, not sea) becomes the site of another enemy\'s destruction. The economic loss for the local pig-herders was considerable — two thousand pigs represents significant capital — which explains the community\'s response in v.17.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The herdsmen flee immediately to report what happened — not just to the town but to the surrounding countryside. The verb "fled" (ephygon) suggests panic, not merely haste. Their report triggers a public response: people come out to see. The scene about to unfold (vv.15-17) is a community confronting the aftermath of an event that exceeds their interpretive categories. They have lost property and gained a formerly dangerous man sitting quietly in his right mind — and they are afraid of the latter more than relieved by it.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The transformed man — sitting, clothed, in his right mind — is the visual proof of what happened. "Sitting" (kathēmenon) contrasts with his previous constant restless motion (day and night in the tombs and hills, v.5); "clothed" implies he had been going without clothing, a detail Luke makes explicit (Luke 8:27); "in his right mind" (sōphrona) means rational, self-possessed, capable of conversation. The community\'s fear at this sight is psychologically precise: what they knew how to manage (the dangerous man) has been replaced by something they do not know how to classify.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The eyewitnesses — specifically those who had seen both the exorcism and the destruction of the pig herd — give the full account to the arriving crowd. The double report (what happened to the demoniac and also about the pigs) implies the crowd was already focused on the economic dimension: the pigs mattered to this Gentile community in a way that would not have applied to Jewish territory. The community\'s subsequent request (v.17) confirms that the economic loss weighs more heavily than the healing in their response to Jesus.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The community asks Jesus to leave — not out of hostility to him personally, but out of fear of further disruption. The loss of two thousand pigs was a community-scale economic event. For a Gentile Decapolis village whose livelihood might depend partly on pig production for the urban markets of the Hellenistic cities, this was catastrophic. Their fear is the fear of further unpredictable power, not the reverent fear of the holy. The contrast with the healed man\'s request (v.18) is deliberate: the community rejects what the individual embraces.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The healed man\'s request to "go with" Jesus (be with him, hina met autou ē) uses the same verb as Mark\'s description of the Twelve\'s appointment: Jesus appointed twelve "to be with him" (hina ōsin met autou, 3:14). He is asking for the same relationship the disciples have — not merely gratitude but ongoing proximity to Jesus. Jesus refuses the request, but the refusal is itself a commission: his attachment is redirected, not rejected. The Decapolis becomes his mission field.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Jesus\'s command to "go home to your own people" and report "how much the Lord has done for you" is striking in context. In Jewish territory, Jesus consistently commands silence (the Messianic Secret, 1:44, 5:43, 7:36). Here in Gentile territory he explicitly commissions proclamation — because the Messianic Secret is a specifically Jewish concern (about premature royal-Messianic enthusiasm), not applicable in the Decapolis. The healed man becomes the first missionary figure in Mark, sent to announce what he himself experienced.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The Decapolis was a circuit of ten (or more) Hellenistic cities — a confederation including Damascus, Gerasa, Philadelphia, Scythopolis, and others — stretching across modern Jordan and southern Syria. The man proclaims throughout this entire region: a Gentile witness to a Gentile audience, before any of the Twelve have been formally sent on mission. The response ("all were amazed") is the standard Markan reaction to demonstrations of power, but here it is wholly Gentile amazement, outside the synagogue framework entirely.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The return crossing to "the other side" brings Jesus back to Jewish territory (the western shore of the Sea of Galilee near Capernaum). The crowd that gathers immediately reflects the pattern of Capernaum and surrounding Galilee: Jesus cannot be in public without drawing a crowd. The double healing narrative that follows (5:21-43) is a classic Markan intercalation: one story is interrupted by another, and the two interpret each other — both involve twelve (twelve years of illness; a twelve-year-old girl), both involve women, both involve the boundary between death and life.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Jairus is identified as archisynagōgos — the ruler or president of the synagogue. This was an elected or appointed lay official responsible for managing the synagogue building, maintaining order during worship, and inviting speakers. It was a position of considerable social prestige in a Jewish community. That Jairus comes and falls at Jesus\'s feet (prosepipton) is a striking social reversal: the synagogue\'s chief administrative officer prostrates himself before an itinerant Galilean teacher whose authority is not institutionally derived. His daughter\'s crisis overrides every social calculation.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The phrase "little daughter" (to thygatrion mou) uses the diminutive, expressing tender affection. His request is for Jesus to "lay hands on her" (epitithēs tas cheiras) — physical imposition of hands was a recognized healing gesture in Jewish practice, used by rabbis and associated with prophetic blessing. The phrase "so that she will be healed and live" (sōthē kai zēsē) uses vocabulary that in Greek can mean both physical recovery and eschatological life — ambiguity that becomes significant when she dies before Jesus arrives.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The crowd pressing around Jesus as he walks — the Greek word sunthlibō (pressed, squeezed) appears only here and in the next verse — sets up the context for the hemorrhagic woman\'s story. The crowd is physically dense, bodies in contact with Jesus. Yet only one touch, from one specific person with specific intention and need, triggers a transfer of healing power. The crowd as background pressure makes the woman\'s deliberate touch against the grain of the movement all the more remarkable.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A woman with a hemorrhage for twelve years: Leviticus 15:25-27 specified that a woman with an abnormal blood flow was ritually impure for the duration of the flow, and that everything she touched — furniture, clothing, other people — became impure. Twelve years of chronic hemorrhage meant twelve years of ritual uncleanness, social isolation from communal worship, inability to touch others without making them impure, and exclusion from the synagogue. She was legally untouchable. Approaching a crowd and touching a teacher\'s clothing was a serious violation of ritual law and a significant social risk.</p>',
    "26": '<p>Medical treatment in the first century combined Hippocratic practice (diet, exercise, bloodletting, herbal remedies) with folk medicine and temple healing. Jewish women suffering from hemorrhage would have had access to physicians whose treatments for such conditions included astringent herbs, cauterization, and various other remedies — none of which were effective for chronic internal bleeding. The observation that she spent all she had and grew worse is not a polemic against medicine but a narrative establishing that human remedy was exhausted before she came to Jesus.</p>',
    "27": '<p>She "heard about Jesus" — the stories of his healing activity (1:28, 1:45, 3:8) had circulated widely enough to reach someone in her social situation, probably transmitted by others who had been healed or had witnessed healings. Her approach from behind (opisthen, in the crowd) is strategic: touching Jesus from the front would require him to look at her, recognize her condition, and be seen to permit or deny contact. Approaching from behind in a crowd allows her to touch and potentially withdraw undetected — the act of someone who knows she is not supposed to be there at all.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"If I just touch his clothes, I will be healed" — her reasoning reflects a widely attested ancient belief in the therapeutic power associated with holy people, transmitted through physical contact with garments, relics, or shadows. The Egyptian magician Papyri record analogous formulas. Jewish tradition associated healing power with the fringe (tzitzit) of a garment (Mal 4:2 LXX: "healing in his wings/fringes"). Her reasoning is neither superstitious nor mechanical — she is attributing a specific power to a specific person and seeking contact with it.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The healing is immediate and proprioceptive — she knew in her body that she was freed from her suffering. The word for "freed" (iaomai) is the standard Greek word for medical healing; the word for "suffering" (mastix, literally "scourge" or "whip") was used metaphorically for chronic disease. Her physical certainty precedes any word from Jesus. The hemorrhage stops at the moment of contact, before any exchange — establishing that the power transfer happened through the touch, not through a verbal declaration of faith.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"Power had gone out from him" (dynamis ex autou exelthein) — dynamis in Greek means both physical power and miraculous power. The phrase implies that healing is not a technique Jesus performs but a power that flows from him, and that even involuntary contact can trigger it. Jesus\'s question "Who touched my clothes?" is not ignorance but an invitation to disclosure — as v.32 confirms, he is looking around deliberately. Mark\'s account preserves this as a spontaneous, real-time event rather than a controlled dispensation of healing.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The disciples\' response — "the crowd is pressing against you and you ask who touched you?" — reflects genuine puzzlement. In a dense crowd where physical contact is constant, distinguishing one purposeful touch from the general pressure seems impossible. The disciples\' practical objection underlines the specificity of what Jesus perceived: not the general contact of a crowd but a particular contact made with particular intent. The distinction between accidental contact and faith-directed touch is apparently perceptible.</p>',
    "32": '<p>Jesus "kept looking around to see who had done it" — the imperfect tense suggests sustained, deliberate looking. The woman knew what had happened and knew that Jesus knew something had happened. The subsequent confrontation is not Jesus hunting for a wrongdoer but creating the opportunity for public testimony. The woman\'s healing was real but secret; Jesus draws her into public acknowledgment, both for her own sake and as a witness to the crowd, including Jairus, who is watching this delay while his daughter dies.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The woman comes "knowing what had happened to her" — the Greek participle (eidyia) is emphatic. She is not uncertain or confused; she knows she is healed. She also knows she has violated ritual law by touching an unclean person to an apparently holy man in a public setting. She falls before him "trembling with fear" (phoboumenē kai tremousa) and tells him "the whole truth" (pasan tēn alētheian). The confession requires her to name her condition publicly, before the crowd, including Jairus and his attendants — an act of enormous social and emotional courage.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"Daughter" (thygatēr) — not a diminutive but the same form of address used between adults. Jesus addresses a ritually impure, socially excluded woman as daughter, publicly, before a crowd that includes a synagogue ruler. The word carries the weight of belonging: she is not cast out for her violation of ritual purity but welcomed into the family of those who belong to Jesus. "Your faith has healed you" (hē pistis sou sesōken se) uses the perfect tense of sōzō — a state of being saved or healed that is now established. "Go in peace" (hypage eis eirēnēn) echoes the Hebrew priestly blessing formula shalom, a state of wholeness and restored standing.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The messengers from Jairus\'s house arrive while Jesus is still speaking — the delay caused by the woman\'s healing has cost Jairus his daughter. "Your daughter is dead; why bother the teacher any more?" reflects the practical calculus of grief: death is final, and continuing to impose on a healer for a corpse is pointless. The word "teacher" (didaskalos) is the form of address used for Jesus by outsiders throughout Mark — respectful but not recognizing his full authority. The messengers are not hostile; they are simply reporting what they believe to be true.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"Don\'t be afraid; just believe" — the command echoes 4:40 ("Why are you so afraid? Do you still have no faith?") addressed to the disciples in the storm. Jairus is in a position structurally identical to the disciples on the boat: facing a situation that appears beyond remediation, asked to maintain trust in Jesus when circumstances argue against it. The command is not addressed to the messengers (who were not asking for anything) but to Jairus, the only person whose response still matters for what is about to happen.</p>',
    "37": '<p>Peter, James, and John constitute the inner circle of the Twelve who witness the uniquely significant events: the Transfiguration (9:2), Gethsemane (14:33), and here, the raising of Jairus\'s daughter. This selective circle of witnesses follows the pattern of restricted access to divine presence in the OT — not everyone could enter the Holy Place, and not everyone could witness what Moses saw on the mountain. The exclusion of others also prevents crowd interference with a scene requiring quiet and focused faith.</p>',
    "38": '<p>Professional mourning was a standard social institution in the ancient Near East and first-century Jewish culture. The Mishnah (m. Ketubbot 4:4) specifies that even the poorest man in Israel was required to hire at least two flute players and one wailing woman for his wife\'s funeral; wealthier families employed many more. These professionals arrived quickly and began their work before burial. The "commotion, wailing, and crying" Jesus finds at Jairus\'s house is therefore not merely spontaneous grief but the organized public expression of a death announcement — the mourning infrastructure already deployed.</p>',
    "39": '<p>"The child is not dead but asleep" — the statement would have seemed either deceptional or deluded to professional mourners who had just seen the child\'s body. Whether Jesus means that death itself is, from his perspective, a temporary state (as 1 Cor 15:51 implies), or that the child was in a coma misdiagnosed as death, the result is the same: he treats the situation as reversible. The mourners\' laughter (v.40) is the appropriate response of professionals to someone who appears to misunderstand their trade. Jesus then expels them — what is about to happen does not require an audience of unbelievers.</p>',
    "40": '<p>The expulsion of the mourners is an act of deliberate social authority in a culture where death rituals were communal and not easily interrupted. Jesus takes charge of the scene: the mourners are put outside (ekbalōn — the same verb used for exorcism), and only the parents and the three disciples are brought in. The restriction creates the intimate setting for the miracle that follows, paralleling Elijah\'s similar withdrawal in 1 Kgs 17:19-20 (and Elisha\'s in 2 Kgs 4:33) before raising a child from the dead. Mark\'s Jewish audience would have caught the prophetic pattern immediately.</p>',
    "41": '<p>"Talitha koum" is Aramaic, preserved here in transliteration — one of the few places in the Gospels where the actual Aramaic words of Jesus are retained. Papias (apud Eusebius HE 3.39) records that Mark wrote down Peter\'s teaching accurately, preserving what Peter said rather than arranging it as a connected discourse. The retention of Aramaic phrases in Mark (also ephphatha in 7:34, abba in 14:36) is consistent with eyewitness memory: Peter remembered and Mark preserved the actual syllables spoken. For a Roman Gentile audience, the Aramaic words required explanation (which Mark provides), but their preservation signals the proximity of the account to its source.</p>',
    "42": '<p>The girl was twelve years old — the same number as the hemorrhaging woman\'s twelve years of illness. The structural parallelism is deliberate: both are daughters (Jairus calls his daughter "my little daughter"; Jesus addresses the hemorrhaging woman as "daughter"), both involve the boundary between life and death (the woman on the edge of social death; the girl on the edge of biological death), and both are restored by Jesus in sequence. The twelve-year span mirrors the girl\'s entire lifetime: she has been a living person exactly as long as the woman has been in chronic suffering.</p>',
    "43": '<p>The strict orders not to let anyone know about this (the Messianic Secret in its sharpest form — resurrection cannot be kept secret for long, but Jesus suppresses it as long as possible) are paired with the practical instruction to give her food. The feeding instruction confirms that the child is biologically alive and functional, not a ghost or vision — and also that she is hungry, because the normal processes of embodied life have resumed. The combination of secrecy command and domestic practicality is characteristically Markan: the miraculous is anchored immediately in the ordinary.'
  },
  "6": {
    "1": '<p>Jesus returns to his hometown (patris, literally "fatherland" or "place of origin") — identified as Nazareth in the parallel accounts (Matt 13:54, Luke 4:16). Nazareth was a small village in lower Galilee, not mentioned in the OT, the Talmud, or Josephus — its population was perhaps a few hundred. It had no strategic or religious significance. The journey with his disciples establishes that this is now a formal teaching visit, not a private family call; he enters the synagogue on the Sabbath and teaches publicly.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The synagogue in Nazareth would have been a modest meeting-hall for the village. Synagogue Torah-reading was conducted by a member of the congregation or a visiting teacher (Luke 4:17 describes the formal procedure: stand to read, sit to teach). The crowd\'s response — amazement followed by skeptical questions — follows the pattern of 1:22 (Capernaum synagogue) but here the amazement turns hostile. "Where did this man get these things?" reflects the honor-shame logic of the village: wisdom and power must have a recognized social source, and no one in Nazareth knows where his comes from.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Is not this the carpenter?" — the word tekton can mean craftsman in wood, stone, or metal; in Galilean village context it most likely means a builder or carpenter who worked with both wood and stone. It is the only Gospel that identifies Jesus himself as a tekton (Matthew 13:55 calls him "the carpenter\'s son"). "Mary\'s son" rather than "Joseph\'s son" is unusual: Jewish patronymics used the father\'s name. One explanation is that Joseph was deceased by this point; another is that the designation carries a subtle social slight (questioning his father\'s identity). The brothers (James, Joseph, Judas, Simon) and unnamed sisters are members of the village community — living there, known to all. The offense is precisely that familiarity: they know his family and cannot reconcile it with his claims.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"A prophet is not without honor except in his own town, among his relatives, and in his own home" — this saying appears in various forms in both Jewish and Greco-Roman tradition, expressing the general observation that familiarity breeds contempt rather than recognition. Jesus applies to himself the classic pattern of Israel\'s prophetic history: the prophets were consistently rejected by their own people (cf. Jeremiah, Elijah, Amos). The threefold expansion (hometown, relatives, household) moves from the widest circle to the narrowest, suggesting the rejection is total at every level of the social network.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Mark states plainly that Jesus "could not do any miracles there" except heal a few sick people by laying on hands. Matthew softens this to "he did not do many miracles there because of their lack of faith" (Matt 13:58). Mark\'s unambiguous statement that Jesus could not — not would not — is one of the more theologically challenging details in the Gospel, and it is honest about the relational conditions under which healing occurred. Faith is not a magical trigger but the relational posture that makes transformative encounter possible; its absence forecloses the encounter, not by limiting Jesus\'s power but by blocking the reception of it.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Jesus "was amazed at their lack of faith" — this and the centurion\'s faith (Matt 8:10, Luke 7:9) are the two places the Gospels record Jesus as genuinely astonished. The amazement is symmetrical to the disciples\' amazement at his power — here he is astonished at the depth of human closure to it. The teaching circuit through surrounding villages is his response: if Nazareth will not receive him, he goes to those who will. The rejection at the hometown does not slow the mission but redirects it outward.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The sending of the Twelve in pairs (duo duo) follows the Deuteronomic requirement that testimony be confirmed by two witnesses (Deut 17:6, 19:15) — two missionaries together can confirm each other\'s account of what they saw and did. Pairs were also practical for safety on the road and for mutual support. The authority given over impure spirits (v.7) mirrors the commission of 3:14-15; they are sent with the same power Jesus himself exercises in his exorcisms. This is delegation of authority, not independent action.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The travel instructions — no bread, no bag, no money — reflect an itinerant mission style that parallels both Jewish prophetic tradition and the Cynic philosophical school, whose teachers (in the Greek-speaking world contemporary with Jesus) similarly traveled with minimal possessions as a countercultural demonstration. The staff was permitted (Mark) while Matthew\'s version prohibits even a staff — the difference likely reflects different regional mission contexts. The instructions create radical dependence on hospitality, positioning the missionaries as recipients of local generosity rather than self-sufficient travelers.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Sandals but not an extra tunic — the instruction creates a profile of deliberate simplicity. The traveling philosopher or teacher with a single garment (often a rough cloak or tunic) was a recognized social type in both Jewish and Hellenistic culture. The Cynics famously wore a single rough cloak (tribōn) as a philosophical statement. Jesus\'s missionaries are not to mimic this exactly — they are sent to specific households, not to perform public poverty — but the minimal outfit marks them as people who depend on God\'s provision through the communities they serve, not on their own resources.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Whenever you enter a house, stay there until you leave that town" — the instruction prevents the appearance of favoritism (moving to a better household when a more prosperous one invites you) and the accompanying social offense to the first hosts. In a Mediterranean patronage culture, accepting hospitality created an ongoing social bond between patron and client; switching hosts would have been understood as a public evaluation of the first household as inferior. The missionaries are to commit to their initial hosts and remain faithful to them for the duration of their stay in any given town.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Shaking the dust off the feet was a gesture of total dissociation. Pharisees returning from Gentile territory would shake the dust from their feet and sandals before re-entering Jewish land — the dust of Gentile territory was itself considered impure. Applied here to Jewish towns that reject the gospel, the gesture inverts the normal direction: it is the missionary who treats the rejecting town as the place of pollution. The testimony against them (eis martyrion autois) is not a curse but a formal witness-act: the rejection has been registered and will stand as evidence at judgment.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The apostles\' preaching that people should repent continues John the Baptist\'s central message (1:4, 1:15) and the content of Jesus\'s own proclamation. Repentance (metanoia) in Jewish tradition meant turning from sin and returning to covenant faithfulness — not merely emotional remorse but a reorientation of life and conduct. The missionaries are not sent to announce Jesus\'s identity (which would trigger premature Messianic response) but to call for the repentance that makes readiness for the kingdom possible.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Anointing the sick with oil was both a recognized medicinal practice in the ancient world (olive oil was used as an antiseptic and soothing agent; Josephus describes Herod\'s body being covered in warm oil before death, Ant. 17.172) and a quasi-priestly or prophetic act. James 5:14 later institutionalizes it as a community healing practice. The combination of exorcism and anointing-with-oil constitutes the full apostolic mission: authority over spiritual oppression and physical illness together, mirroring Jesus\'s own ministry of preaching, healing, and exorcism.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Herod Antipas, tetrarch of Galilee (4 BCE – 39 CE), had divorced his Nabatean wife to marry Herodias, the wife of his half-brother Philip — a marriage John the Baptist condemned as violating Levitical law (Lev 18:16, 20:21). Josephus (Ant. 18.116-119) confirms John\'s imprisonment and execution and adds that Herod feared John\'s popular influence might lead to sedition — a political rather than personal motive. Mark emphasizes the personal vendetta of Herodias. Herod\'s title here is "king" (basileus) — technically incorrect; he was a tetrarch — but Josephus notes he was popularly called king by his subjects.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The popular identifications of Jesus — as Elijah, as one of the prophets, or as John raised from the dead — reflect the categories available in Jewish eschatological expectation. Malachi 4:5 predicted the return of Elijah before "the great and dreadful day of the LORD," and Jewish expectation of Elijah\'s return was widespread and specific (discussed in detail in rabbinic literature). The identification as "a prophet like one of the prophets of long ago" draws on the general expectation of prophetic restoration in the last days (Deut 18:15-18; the "prophet like Moses" tradition). None of the popular options is adequate — they are all markers of the question Jesus will make explicit at Caesarea Philippi (8:27-30).</p>',
    "16": '<p>Herod\'s conclusion — that Jesus is John raised from the dead — is born from a guilty conscience (as Matthew\'s narrative makes explicit, 14:2). The idea that a martyred holy man might return with supernatural power was not foreign to Jewish thought: 2 Maccabees 15:13-16 records a vision of the martyred Onias and the prophet Jeremiah appearing to encourage Judas Maccabaeus. Herod\'s fear identifies him precisely: he knows what he did was wrong, and he is now confronting what he fears is the consequence. The resurrection of John as a punitive agent against him is the specific content of his terror.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The background to John\'s imprisonment: Herodias was originally married to Herod Philip, Antipas\'s half-brother (not the tetrarch Philip of Gaulanitis but a different Philip who lived as a private citizen in Rome). Antipas met Herodias while visiting Rome, and they agreed to divorce their respective spouses to marry each other. John\'s condemnation of the marriage was not merely personal moralizing but a prophetic application of Levitical law: Lev 20:21 forbids marrying a brother\'s wife, and Lev 18:16 specifically prohibits uncovering a brother\'s nakedness. The marriage was a public violation of Torah, and John said so publicly.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"It is not lawful for you to have your brother\'s wife" — John\'s confrontation of Herod is in the tradition of OT prophetic rebuke of rulers: Nathan to David (2 Sam 12), Elijah to Ahab and Jezebel (1 Kgs 21), Amos to the ruling class of Israel. The prophet who speaks truth to the king at personal risk is a recognized prophetic role. In John\'s case the risk was entirely real: speaking against the tetrarch\'s marriage was not a protected religious freedom but a political provocation that Herod could punish — and did.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Herodias "nursed a grudge" (enechein — literally "to hold [a charge] against") and wanted to kill him but was not able to. The word enechein was used in legal contexts for holding a charge against someone awaiting trial. Herodias\'s position was structurally vulnerable: John\'s condemnation was public, and her husband was ambivalent about silencing him permanently (v.20). Her frustration was the frustration of a woman who had given up an existing household (her marriage to Philip) for a new one, and now found that her new husband\'s religious scruples stood between her and the elimination of her most prominent critic.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Herod\'s complex response to John is psychologically precise: he feared him (phobeō — the reverent fear of the holy), protected him (syntēreō — kept him safe), found him confusing (ēporei — was at a loss, perplexed) but liked to listen to him (hēdeōs ēkouen — heard him gladly). This portrait of a man caught between his fascination with a holy figure and his inability to act on what he heard is a recognizable type: attracted to righteousness but unwilling to reorder his life around it. The protection John received from Herod himself was the only thing preventing Herodias from acting sooner.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The birthday banquet (genesion, a Latinism from Latin genesia) was a Hellenistic royal celebration of the ruler\'s birthday, common in the courts of Alexander\'s successors and later Herodian client-kings. These were elaborate formal dinners for the political elite — military commanders, high officials, and prominent regional leaders. The setting was almost certainly Machaerus, Herod\'s fortress-palace in Perea east of the Dead Sea (Josephus, War 7.171-178), where John was imprisoned. The banquet is thus a court event in a military stronghold, not a domestic celebration.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The daughter of Herodias (named Salome in Josephus, Ant. 18.136-137, though not in Mark) danced for the guests. The scene is a reclining symposium — Hellenistic banquets were formal affairs with guests reclining on couches around a central space. Solo dancing at such events was typically performed by entertainers of lower social status; that Herodias\'s daughter performed is either a sign of the informality of the occasion or a calculated strategic move by Herodias to position her daughter as the king\'s beneficiary. The king\'s pleasure and his public offer confirm the performance was successful.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"Up to half my kingdom" — the formula echoes the Persian royal hyperbole of Esther 5:3, 6 and 7:2, where Ahasuerus makes the same offer to Esther. It was a conventional expression of extreme generosity, not a literal legal offer; no one understood it as an actual constitutional pledge. The oath sworn before witnesses (v.23: "he promised her with an oath") was a more serious binding act: in Jewish and Greek legal culture, a sworn oath before witnesses created real obligation and could not simply be dissolved without public dishonor.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Salome\'s consultation with her mother before responding reflects either a scripted collaboration (Herodias had been waiting for exactly this opportunity) or Salome\'s own uncertainty about what to ask. Mark\'s narrative implies the former: Herodias had a specific target in mind and used her daughter as the vehicle. The request — the head of John the Baptist — transforms a birthday celebration into an execution order. The shift from festivity to death is abrupt and deliberate: the narrative does not prepare the reader for this turning.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The urgency of the request — "right now" (exautēs), "on a dish" (epi pinaki) — adds the quality of a calculated public humiliation. Heads presented on platters appear in ancient contexts as trophies of enemies (Josephus records heads sent to courts on multiple occasions, Ant. 14.339); the public presentation at a banquet where the guest list includes the region\'s military and political elite ensures maximum visibility. Salome returns immediately (the imperfect euthys in Mark\'s characteristically urgent narrative) and states the request with the full public weight of the occasion bearing on the king to comply.</p>',
    "26": '<p>Herod\'s distress (perilypos — deeply grieved, the same word used for Jesus in Gethsemane, 14:34) is genuine but overridden by his public oath and the social dynamics of the dinner. "Because of his oaths and his dinner guests" — the guests included military commanders and Galilean grandees; to refuse his sworn public promise before this audience would be a catastrophic loss of face in an honor-culture context where a ruler\'s word, once given publicly, defined his character and authority. The cost of honoring a rash oath is John\'s life; the cost of breaking it is Herod\'s honor. He chooses to protect the latter.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The executioner (spekoulatōr) is a Latin loanword — speculator originally meant a scout or observer in military context and came to denote a soldier of the Praetorian Guard used as a personal bodyguard and executioner. Mark\'s use of this Latinism (one of several in the Gospel: quadrans in 12:42, praetorium in 15:16, centurion in 15:39) is consistent with a Roman audience that would recognize the technical military term. The execution takes place in the prison of Machaerus during the banquet — a few floors below the dining hall.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The head on a dish — publicly presented, handed from the executioner to the girl, handed by the girl to her mother. The chain of custody is choreographed like a formal presentation: each handoff is deliberate. Herodias receives what she arranged to receive. The sequence, with its formal presentation language, mirrors the language of the Passover meal institution and other formal gift-giving scenes — a dark parody of the feast language that surrounds it. Mark offers no editorial comment on Herodias; the narrative itself is the indictment.</p>',
    "29": '<p>John\'s disciples come and take his body and lay it in a tomb — a brief dignified act in the aftermath of the narrative\'s violence. The language parallels the burial of Jesus (15:45-46): his body (ptōma, corpse) taken and laid in a tomb. The parallel is structural: John\'s death foreshadows and patterns Jesus\'s death; John\'s burial anticipates Jesus\'s burial. The disciples\' act of burial is an act of faithfulness to their teacher and a final demonstration of discipleship. They then, presumably, go to find Jesus — the narrative moves immediately to the apostles returning.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"The apostles gathered around Jesus and reported to him all they had done and taught" — this is the only use of apostolos (apostle) in Mark outside the list in 3:14. The word means "one sent out" and is used here in its formal commissioning sense: they have completed a mission and return to give an account to the one who sent them. The report covers both action (exorcisms, healings) and teaching (preaching repentance) — the two dimensions of their commission (3:14-15, 6:12-13). The return is the natural conclusion of a delegated mission.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The account of people "coming and going" so constantly that the apostles had no time even to eat reflects the reality of Jesus\'s ministry in Galilee at this point: his reputation has spread so widely (1:28, 1:45, 3:7-8) that he cannot be in a public place without being surrounded by crowds. The invitation to come to a quiet place (erēmon topon — a desert or uninhabited place) for rest reflects a basic pastoral concern for the disciples\' physical sustainability. The subsequent failure of the retreat (the crowd outpaces them) suggests that withdrawal from the needs of the crowd is structurally impossible in this phase of the ministry.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The attempt to withdraw by boat to a solitary place is a deliberately private act: the disciples and Jesus crossing the lake alone, without announcing their destination. The boat has been a significant vehicle throughout Mark — the calling of the disciples from fishing boats (1:16-20), the teaching from a boat (4:1), the stilling of the storm (4:35-41), the crossing to Gentile territory (5:1). The lake is not merely transport but a place of training, testing, and encounter with Jesus under pressure.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The crowd outmaneuvers them by running overland: seeing the boat\'s direction and running around the northern shore of the lake, they arrive before the boat. The sea-route was approximately 8 miles around the northern end of the lake — a running crowd could cover this in an hour or more. The crowd\'s extraordinary persistence and mobility (they come from all the towns, recognizing the boat) makes the eventual feeding not a chance encounter but the culmination of enormous communal effort to reach Jesus. They deserve his compassion precisely because they have given everything to find him.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"Like sheep without a shepherd" is a specific OT phrase with a specific register. Numbers 27:17 uses it of Israel lacking a leader after Moses; 1 Kings 22:17 of Israel after Ahab\'s death; Ezekiel 34:5 of Israel scattered because their shepherds failed them. The phrase identifies the crowd not merely as needy people but as the covenant people of God whose appointed leaders have failed them. Jesus\'s response — teaching — is the shepherd\'s primary function: to lead, protect, and feed the flock. The feeding of the five thousand that follows is an enactment in bread of what Jesus is doing in teaching.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The disciples come to Jesus at a late hour to point out the logistics of the situation: remote location, the day already spent. Their solution is pragmatic — send the people away to the surrounding villages to buy food. This is the rational response of those who see the situation as a resource problem. The disciples are not being callous; they are being realistic about what they have (nothing) and what is needed (food for thousands). Their solution is entirely reasonable. Jesus\'s counter-instruction will require them to operate on a different logic entirely.</p>',
    "36": '<p>The suggestion to send the crowds to the surrounding villages and countryside to buy food reflects the Galilean geography: the feeding site (probably near Bethsaida, v.45) was within reach of several villages. Market days and local food vendors would have been accessible to a crowd that dispersed to different villages. The plan is humane — send them before it gets too late to walk and find provisions — but it removes Jesus from any responsibility for the crowd\'s need and delegates the problem to the market economy.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"You give them something to eat" — the command is direct and apparently impossible. The disciples\' response — two hundred denarii would not buy enough bread — is a specific financial calculation. A denarius was the standard daily wage for a day laborer; two hundred denarii represents roughly eight months of wages for one person (or one month for a substantial workforce). John 6:7 assigns this estimate to Philip specifically. The amount is not hyperbole but a realistic assessment of the scale of the problem. The disciples have correctly identified the impossibility — and that is precisely the point Jesus is making to them.</p>',
    "38": '<p>Five loaves and two fish — the staple food of Galilean fishing communities. Barley loaves (John 6:9) were the cheapest grain, eaten by the poor; wheat bread was more expensive and associated with higher social status. Dried or salted fish from the Sea of Galilee was the region\'s primary protein source and a major export commodity. The provisions the disciples have found are not a beginning supply but almost nothing: the food of one small group, probably their own travel provisions. The adequacy of what is available is entirely beside the point of what is about to happen.</p>',
    "39": '<p>The instruction to have everyone sit down on the green grass in groups is a scene of deliberate order imposed on what could easily become chaos. Green grass places the event in spring (Passover season — John 6:4 confirms it was near Passover). The grouping instruction anticipates the feeding logistics but also recalls the organizational structure of Israel in the wilderness: Exodus 18:21,25 describes Moses organizing Israel into groups of thousands, hundreds, fifties, and tens at Jethro\'s advice. The image of thousands seated in groups on the hillside deliberately evokes the encamped people of God.</p>',
    "40": '<p>The groups of hundreds and fifties (not thousands) match the smaller units of the Exodus organizational structure. The combination also recalls the Essene community rules from the Dead Sea Scrolls (1QS 2.21-22; 1QSa 1.29-2.1), which organized the community in exactly these units — hundreds, fifties, tens — for the eschatological messianic banquet. Whether or not the crowd would have consciously identified this pattern, Mark\'s audience would have recognized it as a messianic-banquet image: the people of God organized for the feast of the end time.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The four actions — took, looked up to heaven and gave thanks, broke, gave — constitute the standard Jewish blessing pattern for meals: taking the bread, reciting the blessing (berakah, directed toward God: "Blessed are you, LORD our God, who brings forth bread from the earth"), breaking the bread, distributing it. This is what any observant Jewish head of household would do at a meal. The same four actions appear at the Last Supper (14:22) and in the Emmaus narrative (Luke 24:30). Mark does not identify the feeding as a eucharistic event, but the identical action-sequence creates an intentional resonance.</p>',
    "42": '<p>All ate and were satisfied (echortasthēsan — the same word used in Ps 22:26 LXX for the poor eating and being satisfied, and in Ps 78:29 for God satisfying Israel in the wilderness with bread). The fulfillment language connects the feeding to God\'s provision of manna: the wilderness crowd is fed until full, not rationed. The abundance — all ate, all were satisfied, and twelve baskets were left over — exceeds any natural explanation and marks the event as a divine provision rather than a sharing miracle (the alternative interpretation popular in modern commentary).</p>',
    "43": '<p>Twelve baskets of broken pieces of bread and fish — the twelve baskets correspond to the twelve tribes of Israel, a standard typological number. The leftover abundance after the entire crowd has eaten recalls 2 Kings 4:42-44, where Elisha feeds one hundred men with twenty barley loaves and there is still food left over: "They ate and had some left over, as the LORD said." The feeding of the five thousand is the Elisha miracle at the scale of Moses\'s manna: not hundreds fed but thousands, not leftover from twenty loaves but from five.</p>',
    "44": '<p>"Five thousand men" (andres — males specifically) — the custom in Jewish and Greco-Roman census and crowd estimates was to count adult males as the base number; women and children were not counted. Matthew (14:21) makes this explicit: "about five thousand men, besides women and children." The number five thousand therefore represents the minimum; the actual gathering was larger. The census-style counting at the end of the feeding is itself a significant gesture: these are organized, counted, enumerable people — an implicit contrast with the scattering sheep of v.34.</p>',
    "45": '<p>"Immediately" (euthys — Mark\'s characteristic urgency word) Jesus makes his disciples get into the boat. The haste suggests a deliberate interruption of a potentially dangerous situation: John 6:14-15 records that the crowd wanted to make Jesus king by force after the feeding. Jesus disperses both the crowd and the disciples, preventing the political escalation. Sending the disciples ahead to Bethsaida (on the northeastern shore) while he dismisses the crowd alone reflects his deliberate management of the messianic-enthusiasm dynamic.</p>',
    "46": '<p>Jesus going up to a mountain to pray alone is a recurring pattern in the Synoptics (1:35, early morning in a solitary place; Luke 6:12, all night before choosing the Twelve). The mountain setting carries theophanic associations throughout the OT: Moses on Sinai (Exod 19-20), Elijah on Horeb (1 Kgs 19:8-18). Jesus\'s prayer on the mountain after the feeding and before the sea-crossing echoes the Mosaic pattern precisely: the lawgiver prays on the mountain while the people wait below, and then comes down to them across the waters.</p>',
    "47": '<p>The boat in the middle of the lake with Jesus alone on land establishes the spatial separation that structures the miracle. The Sea of Galilee is roughly 13 km wide at its widest; the disciples have rowed perhaps 3-4 km into the lake (John 6:19: they had rowed about 3 or 4 miles). The setting is nighttime, presumably after the fourth watch had begun. The image of the disciples straining alone against the wind at night recalls the storm-stilling of 4:35-41, where they were also overwhelmed and Jesus was absent — here the absence is deliberate, the return is miraculous.</p>',
    "48": '<p>The fourth watch (tetartē phylakē) was the Roman military designation for 3–6 AM — the period just before dawn. Jewish tradition divided the night into three watches; Romans into four. Mark\'s use of the Roman system is consistent with his Roman-audience orientation. "He was about to pass by them" (ēthelen parelthein autous) — the verb parelthein (to pass by) echoes the theophany language of Exodus 33:22 ("when my glory passes by") and 1 Kings 19:11 ("the LORD is about to pass by"). Moses and Elijah both experienced God\'s presence in a divine passing-by; Jesus enacts the divine epiphany pattern on the lake.</p>',
    "49": '<p>They thought he was a ghost (phantasma — an apparition or shade of the dead) and cried out in terror. The Hellenistic and Jewish world was populated with stories of the restless dead appearing to the living, especially at sea and at night. Seafarers in antiquity had a particular tradition of ghost-sightings; the terrifying night appearance of a figure walking on the water would have immediately triggered this interpretive category. Their cry is not the cry of men recognizing Jesus but of men who believe they are seeing the supernatural, and not benevolently.</p>',
    "50": '<p>"Immediately he spoke to them and said, \'Take courage! It is I. Don\'t be afraid.\'" — "It is I" (egō eimi) is the divine self-identification formula. In Exodus 3:14 (LXX) God identifies himself to Moses: "I AM WHO I AM" / "I AM has sent me." The formula appears repeatedly in Isaiah 41-48 as God\'s self-declaration against the idols ("I, I am he," LXX egō eimi). In the context of a figure walking on the water and calming the disciples\' fear, the formula is not merely self-identification ("it\'s me, Jesus") but a claim to divine presence: the one who walks on the sea and stills the storm is the one who said "I AM."</p>',
    "51": '<p>Jesus climbs into the boat and the wind dies down — as in the storm-stilling of 4:39, the cessation of the wind follows his word and presence. The disciples are "completely amazed" (lian ek perissou en heautois existanto, using an intensive construction unique to Mark). The amazement is a response to a repeated pattern — they have seen him calm the sea before (4:41) — but the cognitive connection has not been made. The reason for their failure to understand is given explicitly in v.52: their hearts were hardened.</p>',
    "52": '<p>"They had not understood about the loaves; their hearts were hardened." The phrase "hardened hearts" (pepōrōmenē hē kardia, perfect passive participle) is the same language used for Pharaoh in the Exodus narrative (LXX Exod 4:21; 7:3) and for Israel in Isaiah 6:10 (cited by Mark in 4:12). Applied now to the disciples — not the Pharisees, not the scribes — this is a striking and unsettling judgment. They have witnessed the feeding of five thousand people from five loaves, and the implication has passed over them entirely. The loaves should have taught them who was with them in the boat; they did not learn it.</p>',
    "53": '<p>Gennesaret (Gennēsaret) is the name of a fertile plain on the northwest shore of the Sea of Galilee, roughly 3 miles south of Capernaum and 2 miles north of Magdala. It was known in antiquity for its exceptional agricultural productivity (Josephus, War 3.516-521 praises its mild climate and rich soil that produced every kind of crop). Anchoring at Gennesaret rather than the intended Bethsaida (v.45) likely reflects the wind conditions described in v.48 pushing the boat south along the western shore. The plain was densely populated and the recognition that follows (v.54) confirms this is well-traveled territory.</p>',
    "54": '<p>Immediate recognition of Jesus as he disembarks — the people of Gennesaret recognize him at once. By this point in the Galilean ministry (which is near its climax before the journey south begins), Jesus\'s appearance and the identity of his group would have been known throughout the region. Word travels by the networks of fishing communities, market connections, and synagogue gossip. The recognition triggers an immediate mobilization of the sick, described in the following verses as a systematic regional operation.</p>',
    "55": '<p>The sick are carried on mats (krabbatois — the same word used for the paralytic in 2:4, another Latinism: grabatus/grabattus from Latin) to wherever they heard Jesus was. The logistical picture is remarkable: as Jesus moves through the region, a relay system of word-of-mouth keeps communities ahead of him informed of his location, and families carry their sick to intercept him at each stop. The scale of this operation — running throughout the whole region — reflects both the desperation of communities with inadequate medical resources and the genuine expectation that proximity to Jesus would result in healing.</p>',
    "56": '<p>"The edge of his cloak" (kraspedou tou himatiou autou) — the same phrase used by the hemorrhaging woman (5:28). In the LXX, kraspedon can refer to the corner or fringe of a garment, including the tzitzit (fringes) worn on the corners of a Jewish man\'s outer garment (Num 15:38-39). Malachi 4:2 (LXX) promises that for those who fear God\'s name, "the sun of righteousness will rise with healing in its wings/fringes" — the same word. Whether or not all who touched the fringe made this connection consciously, Mark\'s narrative implies a significance beyond mere superstition: what the woman found by faith, the crowds of Gennesaret seek by reaching out to the same edge of the same garment.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'mark')
    merge_comm(existing, MARK)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'mark', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Mark mkt-context chs 5-6: {total} verses total written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
